"Lockwood M., Fröhlich C.","Recent oppositely directed trends in solar climate forcings and the global mean surface air temperature. II. Different reconstructions of the total solar irradiance variation and dependence on response time scale",2008,"Proceedings of the Royal Society A: Mathematical, Physical and Engineering Sciences","464","2094",,"1367","1385",,,10.1098/rspa.2007.0347,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-42349116391&partnerID=40&md5=eace0bfc4e7b1f916fa312a63314face","Space Environment Physics Group, School of Physics and Astronomy, University of Southampton, Southampton SO17 1BJ, Hampshire, United Kingdom; Rutherford Appleton Laboratory, Chilton OX11 0QX, Oxfordshire, United Kingdom; Physikalisch-Meteorologisches Observatorium Davos, World Radiation Center, 7260 Davos Dorf, Switzerland","Lockwood, M., Space Environment Physics Group, School of Physics and Astronomy, University of Southampton, Southampton SO17 1BJ, Hampshire, United Kingdom, Rutherford Appleton Laboratory, Chilton OX11 0QX, Oxfordshire, United Kingdom; Fröhlich, C., Physikalisch-Meteorologisches Observatorium Davos, World Radiation Center, 7260 Davos Dorf, Switzerland","We have previously placed the solar contribution to recent global warming in context using observations and without recourse to climate models. It was shown that all solar forcings of climate have declined since 1987. The present paper extends that analysis to include the effects of the various time constants with which the Earth's climate system might react to solar forcing. The solar input waveform over the past 100 years is defined using observed and inferred galactic cosmic ray fluxes, valid for either a direct effect of cosmic rays on climate or an effect via their known correlation with total solar irradiance (TSI), or for a combination of the two. The implications, and the relative merits, of the various TSI composite data series are discussed and independent tests reveal that the PMOD composite used in our previous paper is the most realistic. Use of the ACRIM composite, which shows a rise in TSI over recent decades, is shown to be inconsistent with most published evidence for solar influences on pre-industrial climate. The conclusions of our previous paper, that solar forcing has declined over the past 20 years while surface air temperatures have continued to rise, are shown to apply for the full range of potential time constants for the climate response to the variations in the solar forcings.","Climate change; Solar variability; Solar-terrestrial physics","Cosmic rays; Data reduction; Data structures; Earth (planet); Solar radiation; Temperature measurement; Relative merits; Solar irradiance; Solar terrestrial physics; Solar variability; Climate change",,,,,,"Baliunas, S., Jastrow, R., Evidence for long-term brightness changes of solar-type stars (1990) Nature, 348, pp. 520-523. , doi:10.1038/348520a0; Beer, J., Tobias, S., Weiss, N., An active Sun throughout the Maunder minimum (1998) Sol. Phys, 181, pp. 237-249. , doi:10.1023/A: 1005026001784; Beer, J., Vonmoos, M., Müscheler, R., Solar variability over the past several millennia (2006) Space Sci. Rev, 125, pp. 67-79. , doi: 10.1007/s11214-006-9047-4; Bond, G., Persistent solar influence on North Atlantic climate during the Holocene (2001) Science, 294, pp. 2130-2136. , doi:10.1126/ science.1065680; Bonino, G., Cini-Castognoli, G., Cane, D., Taricco, C., Bandahri, N., Solar modulation of the galactic cosmic ray spectra since the Maunder minimum (2001) Proc. Int. Cosmic Ray Conf, 27, pp. 3769-3772. , ed. R. Schlickeiser, pp, Copernicus Gesellschaft, Katlenburg-Lindau, Germany; Briesmeister, J. F. 1993 MCNP-a general Monte Carlo N-particle transport code, version 4A. Report no. LA- 12625-M, Los Alamos National Laboratory, NMBrohan, P., Kennedy, J.J., Haris, I., Tett, S.F.B., Jones, P.D., Uncertainty estimates in regional and global observed temperature changes: A new dataset from 1850 (2006) J. Geophys. R